  "body": "When doing an upgrade command with the --set flag, the provided values are saved in the release.\r\n\r\nE.g.\r\n```\r\nREVISION: 5\r\nRELEASED: Fri Nov 18 20:14:51 2016\r\nCHART: test-0.1.0\r\nUSER-SUPPLIED VALUES:\r\nreplicas: 2\r\n```\r\n\r\nThe problem is that when you run your next upgrade command, even if the --set flag is not used, the user supplied values will be loaded from the server and be re-used. In the case where no override values are supplied I would expect the default value in the values.yaml file to be used, not the override values from the last upgrade command.\r\n\r\nEven more confusing, if you supply a `--set` command with a different override key, then the last value from the server is not used, it replaces it.\r\n\r\nHere's step by step example: \r\n\r\n1. in values.yaml we have \"replicas=1\"\r\n1. we do a `helm upgrade --install` without a `--set`\r\n   * the replicas value used is the default value of 1\r\n1. we do a `helm upgrade` with `--set replicas=2`\r\n   * the replicas value used is 2\r\n1. we do a `helm upgrade` without any --set parameter\r\n   * **the replicas value used is still 2 (notice that we are not using the default value as we would expect)**\r\n1. we do a `helm upgrade` with a different `--set` value like `--set a=b`\r\n   * the replicas value used is 1 (the default value)",
